      "role": "user",
      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That makes sense from a systemic viewpoint. But if we look at the actual crime statistics or behavioral data, some argue that the sheer volume of certain types of offenses in these specific communities suggests there might be more than just \"bias\" at play. Do you think there are inherent cultural or community-level factors that make these groups more prone to criminal activity, or is it purely the external systemic stuff you mentioned?",
